  "prompt": "What is the difference between a shared bandwidth and a dedicated bandwidth?",
  "response": "Here's a comparison of shared and dedicated bandwidth:\n\nShared Bandwidth:\n1. Multiple users or customers share the same network connection\n2. Total bandwidth is distributed among all users\n3. Typically less expensive\n4. Performance can fluctuate based on other users' activities\n5. Lower predictability of network speed\n6. Common in residential and budget-friendly internet plans\n7. Bandwidth can slow down during peak usage times\n\nDedicated Bandwidth:\n1. Exclusively allocated to a single user or organization\n2. Consistent and guaranteed network speed\n3. Generally more expensive\n4. Performance remains stable regardless of other network traffic\n5. High predictability of network performance\n6. Commonly used in business, enterprise, and mission-critical applications\n7. Provides reliable and consistent connectivity\n8. Better for applications requiring steady, high-speed data transfer\n\nKey differences:\n- Resource allocation\n- Cost\n- Performance consistency\n- Suitability for different use cases\n\nChoosing between shared and dedicated bandwidth depends on specific requirements, budget, and performance needs.",
